    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-09-11T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-09-11T00:00:00-05:00" n="350"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d350">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.6231/402</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Under Secretary of State</hi> (<hi
                        rend="italic">Phillips</hi>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-09-11">September 11,
                            1934</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The German Chargé d’Affaires informed me that he had been in touch with Mr. Peek
                    for some time with regard to a proposed barter of lard and German beer; the
                    German Government was now ready, so he said, to accept 15,000,000 pounds of
                    American lard and, in <pb facs="0543" n="443" xml:id="pg_443"/> return, he
                    understood that the Tariff Commission had lowered the duties on German beer
                    sufficiently to make it accessible to this country; he assumed that Mr. Peek had
                    kept the Department informed of these steps, which he hoped would have the
                    approval of the State Department. I said that I had not heard from Mr. Peek
                    lately in regard to this matter, but very likely Mr. Peek would let us have the
                    facts shortly.</p>
                <p>Doctor Leitner seemed to be vague as to the precise details of the
                    transaction.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">William Phillips</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
